Compare_cohorts

Quynh Tran

November 4, 2015

This script was most recently run on Thu Nov 12 11:04:14 2015. This script is to compare the mice body weight across different cohorts. The script also explores the relationship between Pre-fasted weight, weight loss and the weights after HFD.

Weight data from cohort 5 and 6 were read in from ../data/processed/fasting_weights_file.csv.

Weight data from cohort 7 and 8 were read in from ../data/raw/Cohort_7_Raw_Data.csv and ../data/raw/Cohort_8_Raw_Data.csv.

Tukey post-hoc analysis of body weight

[1] Tukeys post-hoc pairwise comparisons of pre-fasted weight [1] Tukeys post-hoc pairwise comparisons of Fasted weight [1] Tukeys post-hoc pairwise comparisons of Fasted weight

Overall, body weight appeared to be normally distributed across different feeding stages, except for cohort 5. This may be due to one or two mice with outlier weights.

Checking the normality of weight loss and weight gain

WL and WG are not normally distributed as shown in the QQ plots, density plots and histograms. Shapiro p-values for WL and WG are 0.0763347 and 0.0124107, respectively. Therefore, Spearmans rho or Kendalls tau correlation coefficient will be computed.

Relationship between Weight Loss after fasting and Weight Gain after HFD

## 
## 1 - alpha = 0.95 two-sided CI for tau:
## 0.182, 0.398

There is a negative correlation between weight loss (or % weight loss) and weight gain (or %weight gain) after HFD in cohort 5 and 6 while the direction of the relationship reverse in cohort 8 and 9. Only the relationship in cohort 9 is significant after Benjamini Hochberg adjustment with p-adjust=0.01536. When combining all 4 cohorts together, there is a 0.25 correlation between WL and WG and this correlation is statistically significant with p-value=2.0110^{-4}. This is likely due to the increase in sample size from about 20 mice in each cohort to about 100 mice in all. A more reliable information to look at is the 95% CI for the spearman correlation coefficient. The . The range of this CI is wide, indicating that we dont have much knowledge about the effect and more information or more murine experiments are needed.

Relationship between Pre_fasted Weight and HFD Weight

## 
## 1 - alpha = 0.95 two-sided CI for tau:
## 0.087, 0.349

There is no correlation between Pre-fasted weight and weight gain after HFD in any individual cohort. All p-values are greater than 0.05, suggesting that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that there is no correlation between init weight and weight gain. When combining all 4 cohorts together, there is a significant correlation between Pre-fasted weight and weight gain after HFD. This is likely due to the increase in sample size from about 20 mice in each cohort to about 100 mice in all. A more reliable information to look at is the 95% CI for the Spearman correlation coefficient. The 95% CI is (0.1380614, 0.4999208). The range of this CI is wide, indicating that we dont have much knowledge about the effect and more information or more murine experiment is needed.

Relationship between Fat mass and HFD Weight

There is no correlation between percent fat mass after fasting and the absolute weight gain, r=-0.062 and p-value=0.657.
